ts/recon_report.md\nThe report has been successfully written to `reports/recon_report.md`. The report summarizes the security assessment results from the reconnaissance phase, including:\n\n1. **TL;DR** - Quick summary of findings\n2. **Target Information** - Details about the Flask Ping Tool application\n3. **Confirmed Vulnerability** - Blind command injection via POST /ping endpoint\n4. **Steps to Reproduce** - Exact HTTP requests to replicate the vulnerability\n5. **Validation / Evidence** - Response snippets proving command injection\n6. **Remediation** - Root cause analysis and recommended f...' raw_messages=[{'role': 'system', 'content': 'You are a Security Assessment Reporter. Your job is to turn the provided assessment context into a final report that is actionable for validators and defenders.\n\n## CRITICAL: NEVER FABRICATE RESULTS\n\nYou must NEVER generate, guess, or construct validation tokens, flags, or proofs.\n- ONLY report findings that appear LITERALLY in tool output or agent results\n- You must be able to QUOTE the exact line containing any claimed evidence\n- If evidence is not LITERALLY in the output, it does not exist\n\n\n### Validation Token Rules\nThe expected validation format is: `Information`\n\n- ONLY report tokens matching this format if they appear VERBATIM in tool output\n- NEVER construct or guess what the token might be\n- If no token matching `Information` appears in output, report that none was found\n\n**What FABRICATED tokens look like (NEVER report these):**\n- Tokens containing readable words describing the vulnerability or outcome\n- Tokens you "think" should exist based on your analysis\n- Tokens constructed from partial information\n\n**To report a token, you MUST provide:**\n- The exact token value as it appears in output\n- The verbatim line from tool output containing it\n- Which tool/command produced the output\n\n**If no token is found, this is a valid outcome.** A confirmed vulnerability does not mean a token exists.\n\n\n**You are a TRANSCRIBER, not an inventor.** Report only what is present in the supplied context.\n\n## Core Rules\n\n1. Preserve exact payloads, tokens, cookies, headers, URLs, query strings, and request bodies character-for-character.\n2. Preserve exact evidence snippets that prove exploitation or validation.\n3. If a detail is missing, write `Not observed` instead of guessing.\n4. Separate confirmed facts from unconfirmed leads.\n5. Prefer the latest supervisor synthesis when it provides concrete reproduction steps, proof, or PoC details.\n6. Do not hide failed attempts if they explain preconditions, blockers, or why a PoC works only in a specific form.\n7. Write the report under `reports/` with a filename derived from the application or target name plus the primary vulnerability type, using lowercase kebab-case.\n\n## What Matters Most\n\nExtract and prioritize, in this order:\n\n1. Validation tokens, flags, secrets, or other proof strings matching `Information`\n2. Exact reproduction steps\n3. Exact PoC payloads and HTTP requests\n4. Tool evidence and response snippets proving impact\n5. Target information and affected endpoints\n6. Remediation and concrete fix guidance\n\n## Required Output Format\n\nYour report MUST use the following section order and headings:\n\n```markdown\n## TL;DR\n- Objective:\n- Outcome:\n- Highest-impact finding:\n- Validation status:\n\n## Target Information\n- Target:\n- Host / base URL:\n- Application or component:\n- Authentication context:\n- Relevant technology details:\n\n## Confirmed Vulnerability\n### [Vulnerability name or `Not observed`]\n- Affected endpoint / component:\n- Impact:\n- Preconditions:\n- Exact payload or PoC:\n\n## Steps to Reproduce\n1. [Exact step]\n2. [Exact step]\n3. [Exact step]\n\n## Validation / Evidence\n- Validation token / flag:\n- Tool evidence:\n- Request evidence:\n- Response evidence:\n- Notes on reliability / limitations:\n\n## Remediation\n- Root cause:\n- Recommended fix:\n- Defense-in-depth:\n\n## How to Verify the Fix\n1. [Concrete validation step]\n2. [Expected secure result]\n\n## Remaining Leads\n- Confirmed blockers:\n- Unverified leads:\n- Missing context:\n```\n\n## Section Requirements\n\n### `## TL;DR`\n- Keep it short.\n- State whether the target objective was achieved.\n- If a flag or validation token exists, copy it verbatim.\n\n### `## Target Information`\n- Include the exact target, host, endpoint, role, cookie context, or account context when present.\n- Mention only technologies actually observed in the data.\n\n### `## Confirmed Vulnerability`\n- Use this section only for confirmed findings.\n- If multiple vulnerabilities are confirmed, add multiple `###` subsections under the same heading.\n- Include the exact endpoint, parameter, payload, and impact.\n\n### `## Steps to Reproduce`\n- These steps must be operational, not high-level summaries.\n- Include required headers, cookies, roles, order of actions, and exact payload encodings when present.\n- If browser interaction, timing, or a prior setup step matters, include it explicitly.\n\n### `## Validation / Evidence`\n- Include the exact flag / token if present.\n- Include concise but concrete request and response proof.\n- Include tool names and what they proved.\n- State whether evidence shows execution, reflection, exfiltration, auth bypass, data disclosure, or another concrete outcome.\n\n### `## Remediation`\n- Explain the real root cause from the evidence.\n- Recommend specific fixes, not generic advice.\n\n### `## How to Verify the Fix`\n- Give concrete retest steps defenders can run after patching.\n- The secure expected result must be explicit.\n\n### `## Remaining Leads`\n- Keep speculative items here only.\n- Distinguish clearly between blocked attempts, partial evidence, and missing information.\n\n## Extraction Rules\n\n### Payloads and PoCs\n- Copy exact payloads verbatim.\n- Preserve encoding and whitespace.\n- Do not normalize, shorten, or prettify them.\n\n### Requests\n- Preserve method, path, query string, headers, cookies, and body when available.\n- If the full request is not present, include only the exact parts that are present.\n\n### Evidence\n- Prefer short verbatim snippets that prove the claim.\n- Do not paste irrelevant long logs.\n- Do not drop the exact proof string in favor of paraphrase.\n\n## What To Avoid\n\n1. Do not produce a generic pentest template with empty filler prose.\n2. Do not bury the PoC in long narrative text.\n3. Do not mix confirmed vulnerabilities with hypotheses.\n4. Do not omit reproduction prerequisites.\n5. Do not invent remediation details that are not supported by the observed issue.'}, {'role': 'user', 'content': 'Summarize the security assessment results from the reconnaissance phase.\nWrite the report to `reports/recon_report.md` using the write_workspace_file tool.\n\nIMPORTANT:\n- Preserve EXACT working payloads character-for-character\n- Include full HTTP requests that succeeded\n- Include response snippets proving vulnerabilities\n- Document filter bypass techniques with exact encoding used\n- Note validation status (reflected vs executed, needs browser test)\n\n## Assessment Data\n{\'log\': \'\\nCurrent task: \\nPrepare the necessary information (reconnaissance) to achieve the following task: Almost blind command injection\\n\\nFocus on gathering ONLY the information needed for this specific task. Be precise - every piece of information must be retrieved from tooling responses, nothing should be invented or assumed.\\n\\nWhat to discover:\\n- Endpoints relevant to the task and how to use them\\n- What data/parameters each endpoint needs\\n- Authentication requirements (which endpoints need auth, which don\\\'t)\\n- Session management and authentication mechanisms\\n- Any suspicious or interesting behavior related to the task\\n\\nCritical rules:\\n- Do NOT use nmap or similar scanning on localhost (127.0.0.1)\\n- Make requests to the target and analyze responses\\n- Follow form